The Stealth Recoil Spring ™ is designed to reduce felt recoil as well as keep the buffer spring from rubbing against the inner wall of the buffer tube. The buffer mass is designed to stay under constant tension against the bolt carrier and the O-ring on the head of the buffer mass prevents metal on metal contact.The Stealth Recoil Spring comes in 5 variations. Under the project leadership of Nikolay Fyodorovich Makarov, it became the Soviet Union’s standard military and police side arm in 1951. Seen throughout various video game classics and the world. “Another excerpt from We Are The Mighty:“If you are a Russian cosmonaut, you’ve got more than a space suit to protect you.The Russians have been packing heat in low Earth orbit for decades.Along with fishing gear and a first aid kit, the Granat-6 survival kit in every Soyuz spacecraft has a Makarov PM semi-automatic pistol and plenty of ammunition.Presumably available to hunt game or provide a self-defense option, the pistol is just one more tool for the space-faring Russian to use if things go wrong.But the Makarov PM – for Пистолет Макарова, or pistolet Makarova in honor of its chief designer Nikolay Makarov – has plenty of down-to-Earth uses.Concealable and compact, it fires the Russian 9 x 18mm Makarov round, which is slightly shorter and fatter than the 9-mm NATO pistol round used throughout the rest of the world. It has a double-action mechanism – if a round is already chambered the pistol can be fired by pulling the trigger without manually cocking the hammer.Even though it is heavy for its size and has a stiff trigger pull, it’s a natural for police work and covert operations. The designer even copied features from the Walther PP (police pistol) designed in 1929, including its size and the shape of the pistol’s frame.Not surprisingly, since its introduction in 1951 the Makarov was frequently the handgun brandished by state security agents in the U.S.S.R. or the old Eastern Bloc when they said, “Comrade, come with us.”Even in the age of polymer-frame pistols, the Makarov has its adherents.Spetsnaz (Russian special forces) team members often carried the Makarov as their sidearm, particularly team commanders, deputy commanders, and radiomen. They sometimes carried a suppressed version of the weapon for so-called “wet works” – kidnappings and assassinations where stealth, surprise, and silence were necessary for mission success as well as personal survival.With the fall of the Soviet Union, many Makarovs flooded the market and eventually ended up in the hands of shooters in the United States.“The Makarov is more reliable than most of the more expensive small pistols, is well made of good material, and is surprisingly accurate,” writes Matthew Campbell, author of 21st-Century Stopping Power: What Works, What Doesn’t, and Why.”####Call or Text (502)299-8382######******Asking $449 OBO, and open to any type of trade. **********

title: For Sale:  US INDIAN POLICE 1889 12 GA TRAP GUN
postcontent: This is a rare United States Indian Police 12 GA Trap Gun with smoothbore. The 1889 is stamped on the butt of the weapon but the weapon is most likely older. Barrel is approximately 22 inches long and is a single shot with an overall length of 39.125 inches. This is a Native American single shot trap gun. On one side it has Benicia Arsenal and the other has Pine Ridge Indian Agency. The trap gun is made by British and the proof marks suggest between 1811-1892. I have more pictures than what Armslist will allow me to post so if you want any of the marks I can send them. I am not sure of the original manufacturere date and the overall condition is good. The mechanics of the firing mechanism seem to work as it should with the hammer have two different cocking positions and the trigger will release the hammer. The trap door open by pulling the pin and it exposes the breach. The serial number is 2868. The rifle is missing the front band that holds the barrel to the stock. This is something that was common with these types of guns and if you research pictures you can see that some of the Indians used some type of cord to secure it in place. I am not looking for any trades at this time. This is a piece of history and would make an excellent addition to anyones collection.

title: For Sale:  Hawken Rifle .54 Toenjes Barrel
postcontent: This is a very special Hawken Rifle, It has a  1 1/8" x 32" .54 Cal. Oval .020 deep rifling. That's right, it's one of the spectacularly  accurate H. Toenjes custom barrels. It was made in 1995-96 and rechecked and proofed by Hugh last year. The proof target is pictured, it speaks for itself. It has a CM-3 beautifully stripped maple stock stained with Aqua Fortis and LMF Walnut stain and finished with many coats of Tru-Oil and cut back between coats for a semi gloss finish. It features a Roller Lock and Roller double set trigger. You must actually shoot the Roller lock to appreciate the Swiss watch like action Bob gets from his locks.. there is just no comparison to any other lock. The rifle has been proofed a second time with 200Gr 2f and a .526 ball and a .024 patch. It has not been shot in and is must be shot to target, it is new and you must do the normal sighting in procedure. For the sake of full disclosure...I had completed the rifle and was doing the final finish and discovered that the ramrod hole drill had run out to the bottom and as I was finish sanding it broke through...I planned this rifle for Hawken Matches so I expected to shoot off a rest or cross sticks some of the time....I thought that a saddle plate would be an ideal solution, it would be an excellent cover for the ramrod problem and add interest to the rifle. It has  13 3/4" pull and apx 3" drop. It feels real good to me and I am about 5' 11". The rifle weighs about 10 1/2 #.I built this rifle to sell at $2000 +, but in consideration of the saddle plate ramrod issue I will sell it at a reduced price.
